{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639481"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:05:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:05:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17772"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17772"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0,0.09,0.78,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10486"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76186"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10486"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61690"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5438"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24474"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76186"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine vaccination. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The nurse is preparing to administer an intramuscular injection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following angles of injection is most appropriate when administering an intramuscular medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["45 degrees","60 degrees","75 degrees","90 degrees","120 degrees"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIntramuscular injections are typically administered at a \u003Cstrong\u003E90-degree\u003C/strong\u003E angle. This angle ensures that the needle penetrates the skin and subcutaneous tissue to reach the muscle, where the medication can be absorbed effectively. Administering the injection at a 90-degree angle helps avoid depositing the medication in the subcutaneous tissue, which could lead to inadequate absorption and reduced efficacy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdministering an injection at a \u003Cstrong\u003E45-degree\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E60-degree\u003C/strong\u003E angle is more appropriate for subcutaneous injections, where the medication is intended to be absorbed more slowly. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E75-degree\u003C/strong\u003E angle is not typically used for any standard injection technique.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E120-degree\u003C/strong\u003E angle is not safe or feasible for injection purposes, being more technically difficult and putting the administrator at risk of a needle-stick injury. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intramuscular injections are typically administered at a 90-degree angle to ensure the medication is delivered into the muscle tissue.","Subcutaneous medications are administered at a 45-60-degree angle."],"references":["Nakajima Y, Fujii T, Mukai K, Ishida A, Kato M, Takahashi M, Tsuda M, Hashiba N, Mori N, Yamanaka A, Ozaki N, Nakatani T. Anatomically safe sites for intramuscular injections: a cross-sectional study on young adults and cadavers with a focus on the thigh. Hum Vaccin Immunother. 2020;16(1):189-196. doi: 10.1080/21645515.2019.1646576. Epub 2019 Aug 23. PMID: 31403356; PMCID: PMC7012163.","Ayinde O, Hayward RS, Ross JDC. The effect of intramuscular injection technique on injection associated pain; a systematic review and meta-analysis. PLoS One. 2021 May 3;16(5):e0250883. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0250883. PMID: 33939726; PMCID: PMC8092782.","Polania Gutierrez JJ, Munakomi S. Intramuscular Injection. 2023 Aug 13. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310581."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61690"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17772"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61690"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T11:11:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T11:11:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10486"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76186"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"d